{"id":"1904.08814","submitter":"Lindsay Childs","authors":"Lindsay N. Childs","title":"Bi-skew braces and Hopf Galois structures","comments":"17 pages, submitted to New York Journal of Mathematics","journal-ref":"New York J. Math. 25 (2019), 574-588","doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.RA","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We define a bi-skew brace to be a set $G$ with two group operations $\\star$\nand $\\circ$ so that $(G, \\circ, \\star)$ is a skew brace with additive group\n$(G, \\star)$ and also with additive group $(G, \\circ)$. If $G$ is a skew brace,\nthen $G$ corresponds to a Hopf Galois structure of type $(G, \\star)$ on any\nGalois extension of fields with Galois group isomorphic to $(G, \\circ)$. If $G$\nis a bi-skew brace, then $G$ also corresponds to a Hopf Galois structure of\ntype $(G, \\circ)$ on a Galois extension of fields with Galois group isomorphic\nto $(G, \\star)$. Many non-trivial examples exist. One source is radical rings\n$A$ with $A^3 = 0$, where one of the groups is abelian and the other need not\nbe. The left braces of degree $p^3$ classified by Bachiller are bi-skew braces\nif and only they are radical rings. A different source of bi-skew braces is\nsemidirect products of arbitrary finite groups, which yield many examples where\nboth groups are non-abelian, and a skew brace proof of a result of Crespo, Rio\nand Vela that if $G = H\\rtimes J$ is a semidirect product of finite groups,\nthen a Galois extension of fields with Galois group $G$ has a Hopf Galois\nstructure of type $H \\times J$.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 18 Apr 2019 14:39:41 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-07-19"}
